I just picked up this gun from my FFL on October 7th, 2014, direct from Sig Sauer in NH. Brand new in the box, MSRP $1,899.00, Sig 1911 Fastback limited edition designed for 5.11 Tactical. They are just about to stop production of these pistols.

The sights are a combination of green fiber optics on top, only visible in the light, and tritium fiber optic 3 dot combat sights at the bottom. They are tritium, only, no white dots, so they are only visible at night. They also have a tactical ledge on the rear sight to rack the slide off belt, table top or whatever is handy.  The pistol is chambered in .45acp.

I ordered this as a carry gun, and changed my mind about carrying something so hideously expensive after I ordered it.  Absolutely brand new, only test fired by Sig. I haven't even opened the slide or messed with it, to keep it absolutely new in the box. 

I am offering this new pistol for only $1,000, so if you've wanted one of these but didn't want to dish out anywhere from $1,400 to $1,900 for one -- if you could even find one -- this is your chance. I'm not a range gun or safe queen kind of guy. If I can't carry it or won't use it for home defense, it goes.

Not much to photograph with it in the plastic, etc., so I'm attaching some photos from Sig's website. Everything comes with as from the factory, and I can even show you the invoice showing that it was shipped directly from Sig on Thursday, October 2, 2014. This is brand new, unracked, etc.

The BDA-380 Pistol was introduced in 1977 (and discontinued in 1997) as a compact and lightweight pistol for police and civilian use. The gun was manufactured in Italy under contract from FN Herstal (Belgium) and marketed as FN model 140DA (in Europe) or Browning BDA 380 (in USA). Some sources said that BDA 380 is a copy of Beretta 84, but close inspection shows some differences (i.e. Beretta 84 has frame mounted safety while BDA 380 has slide mounted safety). The manufacture of the BDA 380 was ceased circa 1997. It was adopted by Belgian police.

The BDA 380 is a blowback operated, double action semi automatic pistol. It has aluminium alloy frame and steel slide. Ambidextrous slide mounted safety switch disconnects the trigger from the hammer when engaged. The pistol featured low profile fixed sightst and was available in either polished steel or blued finish, with wooden grip panels.

title: For Sale:  COP 357 4 shot Derringer
postcontent:
The COP 357 is a 4 shot Derringer type pistol chambered for the powerful .357 Magnum round. It was designed by Robert Hillberg, based on his earlier work on the Hillberg Insurgency Weapon. It was manufactured by the now defunct COP Inc. of 3040 West Lomita Blvd., Torrance, California (COP stood for Compact Off-Duty Police). The double action weapon is only slightly larger than the typical .25 automatic pistol, which made it a good choice for a defensive weapon or a police backup gun.

Construction and operation of the COP 357

The COP 357 is quite robust in design and construction. It is made of solid stainless steel components. Cartridges are loaded into the four separate chambers by sliding a latch that "pops-up" the barrel for loading purposes, similar to top-break shotguns. Each of the four chambers has its own dedicated firing pin. It uses an internal hammer, which is activated by depressing the trigger to hit a ratcheting/rotating striker that in turn strikes one firing pin at a time. Older "pepperboxes" also used multiple barrels, but the barrels were the part that rotated. The COP 357 is unique in that it uses the ratcheting/rotating striker, which is completely internal, to fire each chamber in sequence.

The weapon has appeared in numerous films, including Blade Runner, The Matrix Reloaded, and Bad Boys.

Professionally re-built with an E.Arthur Brown heavy stainless steel barrel, heavy bolt and compensator. Truly a one of a kind Ruger.
